// ============================================================================
= Introduction

The Transformer architecture, introduced by Vaswani et al. @vaswani2017attention, replaced recurrent and convolutional sequence models with a purely attention-based mechanism. Its key innovation — multi-head scaled dot-product attention — enables parallel computation across input tokens while capturing long-range dependencies through learned pairwise interactions.

Since its introduction, Transformers have driven breakthrough results across a remarkable range of domains. In natural language processing, pre-trained Transformer models such as BERT @devlin2019bert and GPT-3 @brown2020language established new state-of-the-art results across dozens of benchmarks. In computer vision, the Vision Transformer (ViT) @dosovitskiy2021image demonstrated that pure Transformer architectures can match or exceed convolutional networks when trained on sufficient data, while hierarchical designs such as the Swin Transformer @liu2021swin improved efficiency for dense prediction tasks.

This survey provides a structured overview of recent advances in Transformer architectures. We organize our discussion around three complementary perspectives: pre-training and transfer learning (Section 2), domain-specific architectural adaptations (Section 3), and efficiency improvements (Section 4). For each area, we identify key design principles, compare representative models, and highlight open research challenges.

// ============================================================================
= Pre-Training and Transfer Learning

Pre-training has been the primary driver of Transformer adoption. The core idea — train a large model on a self-supervised objective using vast unlabeled corpora, then fine-tune on downstream tasks — was popularized by BERT @devlin2019bert and has since become the standard paradigm.

BERT introduced masked language modeling (MLM), where a fraction of input tokens are replaced with a `[MASK]` token and the model is trained to recover the originals. This bidirectional objective proved substantially more effective than the left-to-right language modeling used by earlier models. The T5 model @raffel2020exploring unified diverse NLP tasks into a text-to-text format, demonstrating that a single pre-trained encoder-decoder Transformer could handle translation, summarization, question answering, and classification with a consistent interface.

Scaling has emerged as a critical axis of progress. Kaplan et al. @kaplan2020scaling established power-law relationships between model size, dataset size, and performance, providing a theoretical framework for the scaling hypothesis. GPT-3 @brown2020language applied these principles at unprecedented scale — 175 billion parameters — and demonstrated emergent few-shot learning capabilities: the ability to perform novel tasks from only a handful of examples without gradient updates. More recently, open-weight models such as LLaMA @touvron2023llama have shown that competitive performance can be achieved at smaller scales through careful data curation and longer training, while GPT-4 @achiam2023gpt4 has pushed the frontier further with multi-modal capabilities and improved instruction following.

// ============================================================================
= Architectural Adaptations Beyond Text

The Transformer's sequence-to-sequence design proved remarkably adaptable to non-text modalities. The Vision Transformer (ViT) @dosovitskiy2021image demonstrated that by splitting an image into fixed-size patches and treating each patch as a token, a standard Transformer encoder could achieve competitive results on image classification. While ViT required large-scale pre-training (e.g., JFT-300M) to match convolutional networks, subsequent work on data-efficient training and hybrid architectures has reduced this dependency.

For dense vision tasks such as object detection and semantic segmentation, hierarchical Transformers have become the dominant approach. The Swin Transformer @liu2021swin introduced shifted window attention, which computes self-attention within local windows while allowing cross-window communication through window shifting between layers. This design achieves linear complexity relative to image resolution while maintaining the ability to model long-range spatial dependencies. The resulting architecture has been widely adopted as a backbone for detection, segmentation, and video understanding.

